Examines taxa detected in negative-control samples and assigns each a
contamination sub-type from read abundance and occurrence patterns:
\itemize{
\item \strong{artifact}: very low total reads AND present in very few samples --
likely sequencing noise or index hopping.
\item \strong{lab_contaminant}: predominantly found in negative controls relative to
real samples -- likely introduced during library preparation.
\item \strong{sample_contaminant}: detected in controls but also widespread in real
samples -- may represent genuine biological signal.
}

This is a pure detector: it flags taxa and returns a \link{contam_tbl} without
modifying \code{physeq}. Because \code{sample_contaminant} may be genuine signal, only
\code{artifact} and \code{lab_contaminant} are flagged by default (see
\code{flag_categories}). Use \code{\link[=filter_contam_pq]{filter_contam_pq()}} to remove the flagged taxa.
}
